Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Sierra J House in court with attorney Paul Arbuckle.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:20 PM. Also called 15TR335, 15TR336, 15TR423 and 15TR478. State - resolved - 15CM92 - plead g/nc to only count as alleged with fine of $100 plus costs, on 15TR335 and 15TR423 - amend both to ordinance violations of traffic regulations with $500 forfeitureplus costs on each, 15TR336 - dismissed, 15TR478 - plead as alleged. Arbuckle and House agree. House pleads NC to 15CM92 as alleged. Court amends 15TR335 to county ordinance of traffic violations, pleads NC, finds G, fine of $500.00 plus costs totalling $834.50 - 60 DTP/CO. Court amends 15TR423 to ordinance of traffic regulations, pleads NC, finds G, fine of $500 plus costs totalling $834.50 - 60 DTP/CO, Court dismisses 15TR336. House pldads G to 15TR478 - finds G, fine as indicated on citation ($200.50) - 60 DTP/SL. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights by entering her plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. Arbuckle makes statement. House withholds comment. Court sentences the defendant to $100 fine plus costs, 60 DTP/CO, authorize expungement under 973.015, report to FOSO to submit DNA sample, right to appeal, adjourned.
